# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: direct-current
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In automobiles, a **42-volt electrical system** was an electrical power standard proposed in the late 1990s.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] It was intended to facilitate increasingly-powerful electrically-driven accessories in automobiles, and lighter wiring harnesses.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Electric motors were proposed to be used for power steering or other systems, providing more compact installations and eliminating the weight of drive belts or large wires for high-current loads.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The proposed new standard was exactly triple the voltage of existing "12-volt" systems.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The higher voltage was selected to provide greater power capacity for wiring and devices on one hand, and to stay under the 50-volt limit used as a guideline for electric shock hazard.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The European auto manufacturer Daimler-Benz proposed a *42V* brand name for the conversion.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Although many manufacturers were predicting a switch to 36-volt (lithium-ion battery) / 42-volt (charging voltage) electrical systems, the "42V" changeover did not occur by early in the 21st century, and plans were mostly abandoned by 2009.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators largely eliminated the 2000s cross-industry push for raising the main automotive voltages.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Applications that once were thought to require higher voltages, such as electrical power steering, were subsequently achieved with 12-volt systems.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In the late 2000s, 42-volt electrical components were used in only a few automotive applications, since incandescent light bulbs work well at 12 volts and switching of a 42-volt circuit is more difficult.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In the 2010s, 48-volt electrical systems became popular.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The SAE discussed an increased automobile standard voltage as early as 1988.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] From the outset, the participants in this workshop included suppliers as well as the automobile companies Daimler-Benz, Ford and General Motors.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In September 1995, various electrical systems architectures were compared at MIT using the tool "MAESTrO", and in December 1995, in the "Conclusions" of this study, a future voltage level of approximately 40 V was defined.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In early 1996, the "Consortium on Advanced Automotive Electrical and Electronic Systems" was set up.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] At the ensuing workshop in March 1996, the future nominal voltage of 42 V was confirmed.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In August 1996, IEEE Spectrum published the paper "Automotive electrical systems circa 2005".
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] On the occasion of the October 1996 Convergence in Detroit, Professor John G.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Kassakian (MIT) gave a talk entitled "The Future of Automotive Electrical Systems" as part of the "IEEE Workshop on Automotive Power- Electronics".
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] On March 24, 1997, Daimler-Benz presented the MIT with a "Draft Specification of a Dual Voltage Vehicle Electrical Power System 42V/14V".
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] At the same time as the activities in the USA, in 1994, again at the initiative of Daimler-Benz, the former SICAN GmbH held its first "*Forum Bordnetz*" (Vehicle Electrical System Forum) in Hanover for German automobile companies.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Here too, suppliers were invited to participate at a very early stage, together with all European vehicle manufacturers.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] On September 13, 1996, at the 7th International Technical Meeting for Vehicle Electronics in Baden-Baden, considerable interest was raised by the paper "*Neue Bordnetz- Architektur und Konsequenzen*" (New Automotive Electrical System Architecture and Consequences), presented by Dr.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] On March 6, 1997, BMW presented the "*Spezifikationsentwurf für das Zwei-Spannungsbordnetz 42V/14V*" (Draft Specification of a Dual Voltage Vehicle Electrical Power System 42V/14V) in Hanover.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The work at SICAN GmbH was given decisive impetus by the cooperation between BMW and Daimler-Benz, as witnessed in their joint definition of the European "Load List 2005" and the jointly authored "Draft Specification of a Dual Voltage Vehicle Electrical Power System 42V/14V".
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Volvo has used 42 V for some of its mild hybrids.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The increased adoption of hybrid vehicle technologies in the 2010s led to 48-volt systems being deployed in mild hybrid vehicles, which add electric boost to the typical internal combustion engine (ICE) propulsion, and facilitates some regeneration during braking for fuel savings.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In 2011, several German car makers agreed on a 48 V on-board electric power supply network on top of the current 12 V network and introduced the "Combo plug", a common power plug for DC charging electric vehicles.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] As of 2018, this 48-volt electrical system had been applied in production vehicles such as Porsche and Bentley SUVs, while Volvo and Audi planned to use the 48-volt standard in 2019 vehicles.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In March 2023, Tesla Inc. began production of the Cybertruck with a 48-volt architecture, the first production vehicle to use 48 volts as the system voltage for the entire low-voltage system.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] They have indicated that their next-generation vehicle will also be utilizing a 48 V low-voltage electrical system as well.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Six-cell lead–acid batteries produce around 12.6 volts while discharging, and their corresponding automotive alternators are designed to produce 13.5 to 14.5 volts during charging.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] 42 volts is an approximation of the output of the new standard's charging system.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The present nominally 12 V automotive electrical system usually operates around 13.8 volts, so 14 V is descriptive.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Literature on 42-volt electrical systems often refers to systems powered with a 6-cell lead-acid battery as nominally 14 volts.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Depending on operating conditions, the vehicle electrical system voltage today can vary between 6.5 and 16 V, with a varying degree of ripple superimposed on this value.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The finding of this study was that the highest possible direct voltage was the best alternative.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The limiting factor for direct voltages is a shock-hazard protection limit of 60 V, which must not be exceeded even during voltage fluctuations caused by extreme conditions.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] This limit eliminates the option of an automotive electrical system with a nominal battery voltage of 48 V, because at low temperatures the charging voltage of the battery can attain 60 V.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Also, the price, weight and volume of batteries are influenced by the number of cells, which must therefore be kept to a minimum.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] New battery technologies for automotive applications would not have been available at affordable costs for the 42 V/14 V PowerNet.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Lead-acid batteries are low-priced and have a very "compliant" charging/discharging characteristic.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Therefore, lead-acid batteries would have been used optimised for energy and service life at the lower voltage and optimised for power at the higher voltage.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Another important criterion for a new architecture was that it should allow gradual conversion of loads to the higher voltage system as required.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In a 42 V/14 V system, the 14 V branch should have been freed of higher-power loads and should operate within much narrower limits.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Power electronics is becoming increasingly important in the automotive sphere and will be a decisive factor in the price of future vehicles.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] This criterion was therefore especially important when selecting the most suitable higher voltage level.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Despite the considerable upward trend of power electronics in automotive applications, its share of the market will decline, because growth rates in other market segments are even higher.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] For that reason alone, a specific manufacturing technology for automotive use is inconceivable.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] In intensive discussions with the major semiconductor manufacturers, a voltage of approximately 40 V was found to be advantageous.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] Other arguments for a higher voltage included the reduction of weight in the wiring system, improved stability, and reduced voltage drop.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] With three times the voltage, thick conductors can be reduced to a third of the cross-section, and at the same time the relative voltage drop can also be reduced to a third.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] For the same cross-section, the relative voltage drop is now no more than one ninth.
[src:direct-current/42-v-electrical-system] The voltage level resulting from these arguments was so close to three times the present voltage that 42 V became the automatic choice for the second voltage level.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In the physics of electromagnetism, the **Abraham–Lorentz force** (also known as the **Lorentz–Abraham force**) is the reaction force on an accelerating charged particle caused by the particle emitting electromagnetic radiation by self-interaction.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It is also called the **radiation reaction force**, the **radiation damping force**, or the **self-force**.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It is named after the physicists Max Abraham and Hendrik Lorentz.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The formula, although predating the theory of special relativity, was initially calculated for non-relativistic velocity approximations.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It was extended to arbitrary velocities by Max Abraham and was shown to be physically consistent by George Adolphus Schott.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The non-relativistic form is called **Lorentz self-force** while the relativistic version is called the **Lorentz–Dirac force** or collectively known as **Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac force**.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The equations are in the domain of classical physics, not quantum physics, and therefore may not be valid at distances of roughly the Compton wavelength or below.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] There are, however, two analogs of the formula that are both fully quantum and relativistic: one is called the "Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac–Langevin equation", the other is the self-force on a moving mirror.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The force is proportional to the square of the object's charge, multiplied by the jerk that it is experiencing.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] (Jerk is the rate of change of acceleration.) The force points in the direction of the jerk.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] For example, in a cyclotron, where the jerk points opposite to the velocity, the radiation reaction is directed opposite to the velocity of the particle, providing a braking action.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the source of the radiation resistance of a radio antenna radiating radio waves.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] There are pathological solutions of the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation in which a particle accelerates *in advance* of the application of a force, so-called *pre-acceleration* solutions.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Since this would represent an effect occurring before its cause (retrocausality), some theories have speculated that the equation allows signals to travel backward in time, thus challenging the physical principle of causality.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] One resolution of this problem was discussed by Arthur D.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Yaghjian and was further discussed by Fritz Rohrlich and Rodrigo Medina.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Furthermore, some authors argue that a radiation reaction force is unnecessary, introducing a corresponding stress-energy tensor that naturally conserves energy and momentum in Minkowski space and other suitable spacetimes.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Physically, an accelerating charge emits radiation (according to the Larmor formula), which carries momentum away from the charge.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Since momentum is conserved, the charge is pushed in the direction opposite the direction of the emitted radiation.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In fact the formula above for radiation force can be *derived* from the Larmor formula, as shown below.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Where $\gamma$ is the Lorentz factor associated with v , the velocity of particle.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The formula is consistent with special relativity and reduces to Lorentz's self-force expression for low velocity limit.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The first calculation of electromagnetic radiation energy due to current was given by George Francis FitzGerald in 1883, in which radiation resistance appears.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] However, dipole antenna experiments by Heinrich Hertz made a bigger impact and gathered commentary by Poincaré on the *amortissement* or damping of the oscillator due to the emission of radiation.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Qualitative discussions surrounding damping effects of radiation emitted by accelerating charges was sparked by Henri Poincaré in 1891.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In 1892, Hendrik Lorentz derived the self-interaction force of charges for low velocities but did not relate it to radiation losses.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Suggestion of a relationship between radiation energy loss and self-force was first made by Max Planck.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Planck's concept of the damping force, which did not assume any particular shape for elementary charged particles, was applied by Max Abraham to find the radiation resistance of an antenna in 1898, which remains the most practical application of the phenomenon.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In the early 1900s, Abraham formulated a generalization of the Lorentz self-force to arbitrary velocities, the physical consistency of which was later shown by George Adolphus Schott.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Schott was able to derive the Abraham equation and attributed "acceleration energy" to be the source of energy of the electromagnetic radiation.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Originally submitted as an essay for the 1908 Adams Prize, he won the competition and had the essay published as a book in 1912.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The relationship between self-force and radiation reaction became well-established at this point.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Wolfgang Pauli first obtained the covariant form of the radiation reaction and in 1938, Paul Dirac found that the equation of motion of charged particles, without assuming the shape of the particle, contained Abraham's formula within reasonable approximations.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The equations derived by Dirac are considered exact within the limits of classical theory.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The reverse situation, problems in which the fields are specified and the motion of particles are calculated.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In some fields of physics, such as plasma physics and the calculation of transport coefficients (conductivity, diffusivity, *etc.*), the fields generated by the sources and the motion of the sources are solved self-consistently.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In such cases, however, the motion of a selected source is calculated in response to fields generated by all other sources.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Rarely is the motion of a particle (source) due to the fields generated by that same particle calculated.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Inclusion of self-fields leads to problems in physics such as renormalization, some of which are still unsolved, that relate to the very nature of matter and energy.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the result of the most fundamental calculation of the effect of self-generated fields.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It arises from the observation that accelerating charges emit radiation.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force is the average force that an accelerating charged particle feels in the recoil from the emission of radiation.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The introduction of quantum effects leads one to quantum electrodynamics.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The self-fields in quantum electrodynamics generate a finite number of infinities in the calculations that can be removed by the process of renormalization.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] This has led to a theory that is able to make the most accurate predictions that humans have made to date.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] (See precision tests of QED.) The renormalization process fails, however, when applied to the gravitational force.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The infinities in that case are infinite in number, which causes the failure of renormalization.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Therefore, general relativity has an unsolved self-field problem.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] String theory and loop quantum gravity are current attempts to resolve this problem, formally called the problem of radiation reaction or the problem of self-force.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The above expression can be integrated by parts.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] A generalized equation for arbitrary velocities was formulated by Max Abraham, which is found to be consistent with special relativity.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] An alternative derivation, making use of theory of relativity which was well established at that time, was found by Dirac without any assumption of the shape of the charged particle.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Below is an illustration of how a classical analysis can lead to surprising results.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The classical theory can be seen to challenge standard pictures of causality, thus signaling either a breakdown or a need for extension of the theory.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In this case the extension is to quantum mechanics and its relativistic counterpart quantum field theory.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] See the quote from Rohrlich in the introduction concerning "the importance of obeying the validity limits of a physical theory".
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The integral extends from the present to infinitely far in the future.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Thus future values of the force affect the acceleration of the particle in the present.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The future values are weighted by the factor $\exp \left(-{t'-t \over t_{0}}\right)$ which falls off rapidly for times greater than $t_{0}$ in the future.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Therefore, signals from an interval approximately $t_{0}$ into the future affect the acceleration in the present.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] For an electron, this time is approximately $10^{-24}$ sec, which is the time it takes for a light wave to travel across the "size" of an electron, the classical electron radius.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] One way to define this "size" is as follows: it is (up to some constant factor) the distance r such that two electrons placed at rest at a distance r apart and allowed to fly apart, would have sufficient energy to reach half the speed of light.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In other words, it forms the length (or time, or energy) scale where something as light as an electron would be fully relativistic.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] It is worth noting that this expression does not involve the Planck constant at all, so although it indicates something is wrong at this length scale, it does not directly relate to quantum uncertainty, or to the frequency–energy relation of a photon.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Although it is common in quantum mechanics to treat $\hbar \to 0$ as a "classical limit", some speculate that even the classical theory needs renormalization, no matter how the Planck constant would be fixed.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] To find the relativistic generalization, Dirac renormalized the mass in the equation of motion with the Abraham–Lorentz force in 1938.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] This renormalized equation of motion is called the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation of motion.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Similar to the non-relativistic case, there are pathological solutions using the Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac equation that anticipate a change in the external force and according to which the particle accelerates *in advance* of the application of a force, so-called *preacceleration* solutions.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] One resolution of this problem was discussed by Yaghjian, and is further discussed by Rohrlich and Medina.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Runaway solutions are solutions to ALD equations that suggest the force on objects will increase exponentially over time.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The ALD equations are known to be zero for constant acceleration or hyperbolic motion in Minkowski spacetime diagram.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The subject of whether in such condition electromagnetic radiation exists was matter of debate until Fritz Rohrlich resolved the problem by showing that hyperbolically moving charges do emit radiation.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Subsequently, the issue is discussed in context of energy conservation and equivalence principle which is classically resolved by considering "acceleration energy" or Schott energy.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] However the antidamping mechanism resulting from the Abraham–Lorentz force can be compensated by other nonlinear terms, which are frequently disregarded in the expansions of the retarded Liénard–Wiechert potential.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz–Dirac force leads to some pathological solutions.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Here $u^{i}=(\gamma ,\gamma \mathbf {v} /c)$ is the four-velocity of the particle, $\gamma =1/{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}$ is the Lorentz factor and $\mathbf {v}$ is the three-dimensional velocity vector.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] where $D/Dt=\partial /\partial t+\mathbf {v} \cdot \nabla$ is the total derivative.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] While the Abraham–Lorentz force is largely neglected for many experimental considerations, it gains importance for plasmonic excitations in larger nanoparticles due to large local field enhancements.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Radiation damping acts as a limiting factor for the plasmonic excitations in surface-enhanced Raman scattering.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The damping force was shown to broaden surface plasmon resonances in gold nanoparticles, nanorods and clusters.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The effects of radiation damping on nuclear magnetic resonance were also observed by Nicolaas Bloembergen and Robert Pound, who reported its dominance over spin–spin and spin–lattice relaxation mechanisms for certain cases.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The Abraham–Lorentz force has been observed in the semiclassical regime in experiments which involve the scattering of a relativistic beam of electrons with a high intensity laser.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In the experiments, a supersonic jet of helium gas is intercepted by a high-intensity (1018–1020 W/cm2) laser.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The laser ionizes the helium gas and accelerates the electrons via what is known as the "laser-wakefield" effect.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] A second high-intensity laser beam is then propagated counter to this accelerated electron beam.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In a small number of cases, inverse-Compton scattering occurs between the photons and the electron beam, and the spectra of the scattered electrons and photons are measured.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The photon spectra are then compared with spectra calculated from Monte Carlo simulations that use either the QED or classical LL equations of motion.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] The effects of radiation reaction are often considered within the framework of single-particle dynamics.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] However, interesting phenomena arise when a collection of charged particles is subjected to strong electromagnetic fields, such as in a plasma.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] In such scenarios, the collective behavior of the plasma can significantly modify its properties due to radiation reaction effects.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Theoretical studies have shown that in environments with strong magnetic fields, like those found around pulsars and magnetars, radiation reaction cooling can alter the collective dynamics of the plasma.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] This modification can lead to instabilities within the plasma.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Specifically, in the high magnetic fields typical of these astrophysical objects, the momentum distribution of particles is bunched and becomes anisotropic due to radiation reaction forces, potentially driving plasma instabilities and affecting overall plasma behavior.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] Among these instabilities, the firehose instability can arise due to the anisotropic pressure, and electron cyclotron maser due to population inversion in the rings.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] An alternate mechanism for radiation reaction on a point charge accelerated by an external force, is that the charge's increase in energy is diminished by the energy carried away by electromagnetic radiation.
[src:direct-current/abraham-lorentz-force] This reduces the particle's acceleration without an additional force, and the paradoxes it causes are not there.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:direct-current/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In electricity generation, a **generator**, also called an **electric generator**, **electrical generator**, and **electromagnetic generator** is an electromechanical device that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy for use in an external circuit.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In most generators which are rotating machines, a source of kinetic power rotates the generator's shaft, and the generator produces an electric current at its output terminals which flows through an external circuit, powering electrical loads.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Sources of mechanical energy used to drive generators include steam turbines, gas turbines, water turbines, internal combustion engines, wind turbines and even hand cranks.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Generators produce nearly all of the electric power for worldwide electric power grids.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The first electromagnetic generator, the Faraday disk, was invented in 1831 by British scientist Michael Faraday.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The reverse conversion of electrical energy into mechanical energy is done by an electric motor, and motors and generators are very similar.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Some motors can be used in a "backward" sense as generators, if their shaft is rotated they will generate electric power.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In addition to its most common usage for electromechanical generators described above, the term generator is also used for photovoltaic, fuel cell, and magnetohydrodynamic powered devices that use solar power and chemical fuels, respectively, to generate electrical power.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Electromagnetic generators fall into one of two broad categories, dynamos and alternators.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The armature can be on either the rotor or the stator, depending on the design, with the field coil or magnet on the other part.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Before the connection between magnetism and electricity was discovered, electrostatic generators were invented.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] They operated on electrostatic principles, by using moving electrically charged belts, plates and disks that carried charge to a high potential electrode.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The charge was generated using either of two mechanisms: electrostatic induction or the triboelectric effect.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Such generators generated very high voltage and low current.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Because of their inefficiency and the difficulty of insulating machines that produced very high voltages, electrostatic generators had low power ratings, and were never used for generation of commercially significant quantities of electric power.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Their only practical applications were to power early X-ray tubes, and later in some atomic particle accelerators.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The operating principle of electromagnetic generators was discovered in the years of 1831–1832 by Michael Faraday.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The principle, later called Faraday's law of induction, is that an electromotive force is generated in an electrical conductor which encircles a varying magnetic flux.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Faraday also built the first electromagnetic generator, called the Faraday disk; a type of homopolar generator, using a copper disc rotating between the poles of a horseshoe magnet.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This design was inefficient, due to self-cancelling counterflows of current in regions of the disk that were not under the influence of the magnetic field.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] While current was induced directly underneath the magnet, the current would circulate backwards in regions that were outside the influence of the magnetic field.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This counterflow limited the power output to the pickup wires and induced waste heating of the copper disc.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Later homopolar generators would solve this problem by using an array of magnets arranged around the disc perimeter to maintain a steady field effect in one current-flow direction.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Another disadvantage was that the output voltage was very low, due to the single current path through the magnetic flux.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Experimenters found that using multiple turns of wire in a coil could produce higher, more useful voltages.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Since the output voltage is proportional to the number of turns, generators could be easily designed to produce any desired voltage by varying the number of turns.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Wire windings became a basic feature of all subsequent generator designs.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Independently of Faraday, Ányos Jedlik started experimenting in 1827 with the electromagnetic rotating devices which he called electromagnetic self-rotors.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In the prototype of the single-pole electric starter (finished between 1852 and 1854) both the stationary and the revolving parts were electromagnetic.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] It was also the discovery of the principle of dynamo self-excitation, which replaced permanent magnet designs.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] He also may have formulated the concept of the dynamo in 1861 (before Siemens and Wheatstone) but did not patent it as he thought he was not the first to realize this.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A coil of wire rotating in a magnetic field produces a current which changes direction with each 180° rotation, an alternating current (AC).
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] However many early uses of electricity required direct current (DC).
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In the first practical electric generators, called *dynamos*, the AC was converted into DC with a *commutator*, a set of rotating switch contacts on the armature shaft.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The commutator reversed the connection of the armature winding to the circuit every 180° rotation of the shaft, creating a pulsing DC current.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] One of the first dynamos was built by Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The dynamo was the first electrical generator capable of delivering power for industry.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The Woolrich Electrical Generator of 1844, now in Thinktank, Birmingham Science Museum, is the earliest electrical generator used in an industrial process.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] It was used by the firm of Elkingtons for commercial electroplating.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The modern dynamo, fit for use in industrial applications, was invented independently by Sir Charles Wheatstone, Werner von Siemens and Samuel Alfred Varley.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Varley took out a patent on 24 December 1866, while Siemens and Wheatstone both announced their discoveries on 17 January 1867 by delivering papers at the Royal Society.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The "dynamo-electric machine" employed self-powering electromagnetic field coils rather than permanent magnets to create the stator field.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Wheatstone's design was similar to Siemens', with the difference that in the Siemens design the stator electromagnets were in series with the rotor, but in Wheatstone's design they were in parallel.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The use of electromagnets rather than permanent magnets greatly increased the power output of a dynamo and enabled high power generation for the first time.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This invention led directly to the first major industrial uses of electricity.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] For example, in the 1870s Siemens used electromagnetic dynamos to power electric arc furnaces for the production of metals and other materials.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The dynamo machine that was developed consisted of a stationary structure, which provides the magnetic field, and a set of rotating windings which turn within that field.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] On larger machines the constant magnetic field is provided by one or more electromagnets, which are usually called field coils.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Large power generation dynamos are now rarely seen due to the now nearly universal use of alternating current for power distribution.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Before the adoption of AC, very large direct-current dynamos were the only means of power generation and distribution.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] AC has come to dominate due to the ability of AC to be easily transformed to and from very high voltages to permit low losses over large distances.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Through a series of discoveries, the dynamo was succeeded by many later inventions, especially the AC alternator, which was capable of generating alternating current.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] It is commonly known to be the Synchronous Generators (SGs).
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The synchronous machines are directly connected to the grid and need to be properly synchronized during startup.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Moreover, they are excited with special control to enhance the stability of the power system.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from Michael Faraday's original discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Faraday himself built an early alternator.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] His machine was a "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar*: each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Large two-phase alternating current generators were built by a British electrician, J.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The first public demonstration of an "alternator system" was given by William Stanley Jr., an employee of Westinghouse Electric in 1886.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti established *Ferranti, Thompson and Ince* in 1882, to market his *Ferranti-Thompson Alternator*, invented with the help of renowned physicist Lord Kelvin.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] His early alternators produced frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Ferranti went on to design the Deptford Power Station for the London Electric Supply Corporation in 1887 using an alternating current system.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] On its completion in 1891, it was the first truly modern power station, supplying high-voltage AC power that was then "stepped down" for consumer use on each street.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This basic system remains in use today around the world.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Later alternators were designed for varying alternating-current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz, for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting and electric motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] As the requirements for larger scale power generation increased, a new limitation rose: the magnetic fields available from permanent magnets.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Diverting a small amount of the power generated by the generator to an electromagnetic field coil mounted on the rotor allowed the generator to produce substantially more power.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This concept was dubbed self-excitation.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The field coils are connected in series or parallel with the armature winding.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] When the generator first starts to turn, the small amount of remanent magnetism present in the iron core provides a magnetic field to get it started, generating a small current in the armature.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This flows through the field coils, creating a larger magnetic field which generates a larger armature current.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This "bootstrap" process continues until the magnetic field in the core levels off due to saturation and the generator reaches a steady state power output.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Very large power station generators often utilize a separate smaller generator to excite the field coils of the larger.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In the event of a severe widespread power outage where islanding of power stations has occurred, the stations may need to perform a black start to excite the fields of their largest generators, in order to restore customer power service.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A dynamo uses commutators to produce direct current.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] It is self-excited, i.e. its field electromagnets are powered by the machine's own output.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Other types of DC generators use a separate source of direct current to energize their field magnets.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A homopolar generator is a DC electrical generator comprising an electrically conductive disc or cylinder rotating in a plane perpendicular to a uniform static magnetic field.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A potential difference is created between the center of the disc and the rim (or ends of the cylinder), the electrical polarity depending on the direction of rotation and the orientation of the field.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] It is also known as a **unipolar generator**, **acyclic generator**, **disk dynamo**, or **Faraday disc**.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The voltage is typically low, on the order of a few volts in the case of small demonstration models, but large research generators can produce hundreds of volts, and some systems have multiple generators in series to produce an even larger voltage.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] They are unusual in that they can produce tremendous electric current, some more than a million amperes, because the homopolar generator can be made to have very low internal resistance.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A magnetohydrodynamic generator directly extracts electric power from moving hot gases through a magnetic field, without the use of rotating electromagnetic machinery.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] MHD generators were originally developed because the output of a plasma MHD generator is a flame, well able to heat the boilers of a steam power plant.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The first practical design was the AVCO Mk.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The U.S. government funded substantial development, culminating in a 25 MW demonstration plant in 1987.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In the Soviet Union from 1972 until the late 1980s, the MHD plant U 25 was in regular utility operation on the Moscow power system with a rating of 25 MW, the largest MHD plant rating in the world at that time.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] MHD generators operated as a topping cycle are currently (2007) less efficient than combined cycle gas turbines.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Induction AC motors may be used as generators, turning mechanical energy into electric current.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Induction generators operate by mechanically turning their rotor faster than the simultaneous speed, giving negative slip.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A regular AC non-simultaneous motor usually can be used as a generator, without any changes to its parts.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Induction generators are useful in applications like minihydro power plants, wind turbines, or in reducing high-pressure gas streams to lower pressure, because they can recover energy with relatively simple controls.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] They do not require another circuit to start working because the turning magnetic field is provided by induction from the one they have.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] They also do not require speed governor equipment as they inherently operate at the connected grid frequency.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] An induction generator must be powered with a leading voltage; this is usually done by connection to an electrical grid, or by powering themselves with phase correcting capacitors.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In the simplest form of linear electric generator, a sliding magnet moves back and forth through a solenoid, a copper wire or a coil.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] An alternating current is induced in the wire, or loops of wire, by Faraday's law of induction each time the magnet slides through.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This type of generator is used in the Faraday flashlight.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Larger linear electricity generators are used in wave power schemes.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Grid-connected generators deliver power at a constant frequency.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] For generators of the synchronous or induction type, the prime mover speed turning the generator shaft must be at a particular speed (or narrow range of speed) to deliver power at the required utility frequency.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Mechanical speed-regulating devices may waste a significant fraction of the input energy to maintain a required fixed frequency.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Where it is impractical or undesired to tightly regulate the speed of the prime mover, doubly fed electric machines may be used as generators.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] With the assistance of power electronic devices, these can regulate the output frequency to a desired value over a wider range of generator shaft speeds.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Alternatively, a standard generator can be used with no attempt to regulate frequency, and the resulting power converted to the desired output frequency with a rectifier and converter combination.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Allowing a wider range of prime mover speeds can improve the overall energy production of an installation, at the cost of more complex generators and controls.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] For example, where a wind turbine operating at fixed frequency might be required to spill energy at high wind speeds, a variable speed system can allow recovery of energy contained during periods of high wind speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A *power station*, also known as a *power plant* or *powerhouse* and sometimes *generating station* or *generating plant*, is an industrial facility that generates electricity.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Most power stations contain one or more generators, or spinning machines converting mechanical power into three-phase electrical power.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The relative motion between a magnetic field and a conductor creates an electric current.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The energy source harnessed to turn the generator varies widely.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Most power stations in the world burn fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas to generate electricity.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Cleaner sources include nuclear power, and increasingly use renewables such as the sun, wind, waves and running water.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Motor vehicles require electrical energy to power their instrumentation, keep the engine itself operating, and recharge their batteries.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Until about the 1960s motor vehicles tended to use DC generators (dynamos) with electromechanical regulators.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Following the historical trend above and for many of the same reasons, these have now been replaced by alternators with built-in rectifier circuits.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Bicycles require energy to power running lights and other equipment.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] There are two common kinds of generator in use on bicycles: bottle dynamos which engage the bicycle's tire on an as-needed basis, and hub dynamos which are directly attached to the bicycle's drive train.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The name is conventional as they are small permanent-magnet alternators, not self-excited DC machines as are dynamos.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Some electric bicycles are capable of regenerative braking, where the drive motor is used as a generator to recover some energy during braking.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Sailing boats may use a water- or wind-powered generator to trickle-charge the batteries.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A small propeller, wind turbine or turbine is connected to a low-power generator to supply currents at typical wind or cruising speeds.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Recreational vehicles need an extra power supply to power their onboard accessories, including air conditioning units, and refrigerators.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] An RV power plug is connected to the electric generator to obtain a stable power supply.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Electric scooters with regenerative braking have become popular all over the world.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Engineers use kinetic energy recovery systems on the scooter to reduce energy consumption and increase its range up to 40-60% by simply recovering energy using the magnetic brake, which generates electric energy for further use.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Modern vehicles reach speed up to 25–30 km/h and can run up to 35–40 km.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] An *engine–generator* is the combination of an electrical generator and an engine (prime mover) mounted together to form a single piece of self-contained equipment.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The engines used are usually piston engines, but gas turbines can also be used, and there are even hybrid diesel-gas units, called dual-fuel units.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Many different versions of engine–generators are available – ranging from very small portable petrol powered sets to large turbine installations.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The primary advantage of engine–generators is the ability to independently supply electricity, allowing the units to serve as backup power sources.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A generator can also be driven by human muscle power (for instance, in field radio station equipment).
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Human powered electric generators are commercially available, and have been the project of some DIY enthusiasts.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Typically operated by means of pedal power, a converted bicycle trainer, or a foot pump, such generators can be practically used to charge batteries, and in some cases are designed with an integral inverter.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] An average "healthy human" can produce a steady 75 watts (0.1 horsepower) for a full eight hour period, while a "first class athlete" can produce approximately 298 watts (0.4 horsepower) for a similar period, at the end of which an undetermined period of rest and recovery will be required.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] At 298 watts, the average "healthy human" becomes exhausted within 10 minutes.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The net electrical power that can be produced will be less due to the inefficiency of the generator.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Portable radio receivers with cranks are made to reduce battery purchase requirements; see Clockwork radio.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] During the mid 20th century, pedal-powered radios were used throughout the Australian outback, to provide schooling (School of the Air), medical and other needs in remote stations and towns.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] A tachogenerator is an electromechanical device which produces an output voltage proportional to its shaft speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] It may be used for a speed indicator or in a feedback speed control system.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Tachogenerators are frequently used to power tachometers to measure the speeds of electric motors, engines, and the equipment they power.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] Generators generate voltage roughly proportional to shaft speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] With precise construction and design, generators can be built to produce very precise voltages for certain ranges of shaft speeds.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] An equivalent circuit of a generator and load is shown in the adjacent diagram.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The generator is represented by an abstract generator consisting of an ideal voltage source and an internal impedance.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] The generator's $V_{\text{G}}$ and $R_{\text{G}}$ parameters can be determined by measuring the winding resistance (corrected to operating temperature), and measuring the open-circuit and loaded voltage for a defined current load.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] This is the simplest model of a generator, further elements may need to be added for an accurate representation.
[src:direct-current/ac-generator] In particular, inductance can be added to allow for the machine's windings and magnetic leakage flux, but a full representation can become much more complex than this.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] An **AC motor** is an electric motor driven by an alternating current (AC).
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The AC motor commonly consists of two basic parts, an outside stator having coils supplied with alternating current to produce a rotating magnetic field, and an inside rotor attached to the output shaft producing a second rotating magnetic field.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The rotor magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets, reluctance saliency, or DC or AC electrical windings.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Less common, AC linear motors operate on similar principles as rotating motors but have their stationary and moving parts arranged in a straight line configuration, producing linear motion instead of rotation.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The two main types of AC motors are induction motors and synchronous motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The induction motor (or asynchronous motor) always relies on a small difference in speed between the stator rotating magnetic field and the rotor shaft speed called slip to induce rotor current in the rotor AC winding.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] As a result, the induction motor cannot produce torque near synchronous speed where induction (or slip) is irrelevant or ceases to exist.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In contrast, the synchronous motor does not rely on slip-induction for operation and uses either permanent magnets, salient poles (having projecting magnetic poles), or an independently excited rotor winding.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The synchronous motor produces its rated torque at exactly synchronous speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed synchronous motor system has an independently excited rotor winding that does not rely on the principles of slip-induction of current.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed motor is a synchronous motor that can function exactly at the supply frequency or sub to super multiple of the supply frequency.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Other types of motors include eddy current motors, and AC and DC mechanically commutated machines in which speed is dependent on voltage and winding connection.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Alternating current technology was rooted in Michael Faraday's and Joseph Henry's 1830–31 discovery that a changing magnetic field can induce an electric current in a circuit.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Faraday is usually given credit for this discovery since he published his findings first.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In 1832, French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii generated a crude form of alternating current when he designed and built the first alternator.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] It consisted of a revolving horseshoe magnet passing over two wound-wire coils.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Because of AC's advantages in long-distance high voltage transmission, there were many inventors in the United States and Europe during the late 19th century trying to develop workable AC motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The first person to conceive of a rotating magnetic field was Walter Baily, who gave a workable demonstration of his battery-operated polyphase motor aided by a commutator on 28 June 1879, to the Physical Society of London.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Describing an apparatus nearly identical to Baily's, French electrical engineer Marcel Deprez published a paper in 1880 that identified the rotating magnetic field principle and that of a two-phase AC system of currents to produce it.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Never practically demonstrated, the design was flawed, as one of the two currents was “furnished by the machine itself.” In 1886, English-born American engineer Elihu Thomson built an AC motor by expanding upon the induction-repulsion principle and his wattmeter.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In 1887, American inventor Charles Schenk Bradley was the first to patent a two-phase AC power transmission with four wires.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] "Commutatorless" alternating current induction motors seem to have been independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In 1888, Ferraris published his research to the Royal Academy of Sciences in Turin, where he detailed the foundations of motor operation; Tesla, in the same year, was granted a United States patent for his own motor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Working from Ferraris's experiments, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky introduced the first three-phase induction motor in 1890, a much more capable design that became the prototype used in Europe and the U.S.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] He also invented the first three-phase generator and transformer and combined them into the first complete AC three-phase system in 1891.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The three-phase motor design was also worked on by the Swiss engineer Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown, and other three-phase AC systems were developed by German technician Friedrich August Haselwander and Swedish engineer Jonas Wenström.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] If the rotor of a squirrel cage motor were to run at the true synchronous speed, the flux in the rotor at any given place on the rotor would not change, and no current would be created in the squirrel cage.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] For this reason, ordinary squirrel-cage motors run at some tens of revolutions per minute (RPM) slower than synchronous speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Because the rotating field (or equivalent pulsating field) effectively rotates faster than the rotor, it could be said to *slip* past the surface of the rotor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The difference between synchronous speed and actual speed is called **slip**, and loading the motor increases the amount of slip as the motor slows down slightly.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Even with no load, internal mechanical losses prevent the slip from being zero.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The constant 120 results from combining the conversions of 60 seconds per minute and that each phase requires 2 poles.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Actual RPM for an induction motor will be less than this calculated synchronous speed by an amount known as *slip*, that increases with the torque produced.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] With no load, the speed will be very close to synchronous.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] When loaded, standard motors have between 2–3% slip, special motors may have up to 7% slip, and a class of motors known as *torque motors* are rated to operate at 100% slip (i.e., 0 rpm, full stall).
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] As an example, a typical four-pole motor running on 60 Hz might have a nameplate rating of 1725 rpm at full load, while its calculated speed is 1800 rpm.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The speed in this type of motor has traditionally been altered by having additional sets of coils or poles in the motor that can be switched on and off to change the speed of magnetic field rotation.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] However, developments in power electronics mean that the frequency of the power supply can also now be varied to provide a smoother control of the motor speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This kind of rotor is the basic hardware for induction regulators, which is an exception of the use of rotating magnetic field as pure electrical (not electromechanical) application.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Most common AC motors use the squirrel-cage rotor, which will be found in virtually all domestic and light industrial alternating current motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The squirrel-cage refers to the rotating exercise cage for pet animals.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The motor takes its name from the shape of its rotor "windings"- a ring at either end of the rotor, with bars connecting the rings running the length of the rotor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] It is typically cast aluminum or copper poured between the iron laminates of the rotor, and usually only the end rings will be visible.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The vast majority of the rotor currents will flow through the bars rather than the higher-resistance and usually varnished laminates.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Very low voltages at very high currents are typical in the bars and end rings; high efficiency motors will often use cast copper to reduce the resistance in the rotor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In operation, the squirrel-cage motor may be viewed as a transformer with a rotating secondary.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] When the rotor is not rotating in sync with the magnetic field, large rotor currents are induced; the large rotor currents magnetize the rotor and interact with the stator's magnetic fields to bring the rotor almost into synchronization with the stator's field.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] An unloaded squirrel-cage motor at rated no-load speed will consume electrical power only to maintain rotor speed against friction and resistance losses.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] As the mechanical load increases, so will the electrical load – the electrical load is inherently related to the mechanical load.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This is similar to a transformer, where the primary's electrical load is related to the secondary's electrical load.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This is why a squirrel-cage blower motor may cause household lights to dim upon starting, but does not dim the lights on startup when its fan belt (and therefore mechanical load) is removed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Furthermore, a stalled squirrel-cage motor (overloaded or with a jammed shaft) will consume current limited only by circuit resistance as it attempts to start.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Unless something else limits the current (or cuts it off completely) overheating and destruction of the winding insulation is the likely outcome.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Many washing machines, dishwashers, larger standalone fans, compressors, etc. use some variant of a squirrel-cage motor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] An alternate design, called the wound rotor motor, is used when variable speed is required.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In this case, the rotor has the same number of poles as the stator and the windings are made of wire, connected to slip rings on the shaft.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Carbon brushes connect the slip rings to a controller such as a variable resistor that allows changing the motor's slip rate.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In certain high-power variable-speed wound rotor drives, the slip-frequency energy is captured, rectified, and returned to the power supply through an inverter.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] With bidirectionally controlled power, the wound rotor becomes an active participant in the energy conversion process, with the wound rotor doubly fed configuration showing twice the power density.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Compared to squirrel cage rotors, wound rotor motors are expensive and require maintenance of the slip rings and brushes, but they were the standard form for variable speed control before the advent of compact power electronic devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Transistorized inverters with variable-frequency drive can now be used for speed control, and wound rotor motors are becoming less common.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Several methods of starting a polyphase motor are used.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Where a large inrush current and high starting torque can be permitted, the motor can be started across the line, by applying full line voltage to the terminals (direct-on-line, DOL).
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Where it is necessary to limit the starting inrush current (where the motor is large compared with the short-circuit capacity of the supply), the motor is started at reduced voltage using either series inductors, an autotransformer, thyristors, or other devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A technique sometimes used is star-delta (YΔ) starting, where the motor coils are initially connected in star configuration for acceleration of the load, then switched to delta configuration when the load is up to speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This technique is more common in Europe than in North America.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Transistorized drives can directly vary the applied voltage as required by the starting characteristics of the motor and load.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This type of motor is becoming more common in traction applications such as locomotives, where it is known as the asynchronous traction motor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] 2. a control-voltage (AC) winding in quadrature (i.e., 90 degrees phase shifted) with the main winding so as to produce a rotating magnetic field.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Reversing phase makes the motor reverse.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] An AC servo amplifier, a linear power amplifier, feeds the control winding.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The electrical resistance of the rotor is made high intentionally so that the speed–torque curve is fairly linear.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Two-phase servo motors are inherently high-speed, low-torque devices, heavily geared down to drive the load.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Single-phase motors do not have a unique rotating magnetic field like multi-phase motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The field alternates (reverses polarity) between pole pairs and can be viewed as two fields rotating in opposite directions.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] They require a secondary magnetic field that causes the rotor to move in a specific direction.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] After starting, the alternating stator field is in relative rotation with the rotor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A common single-phase motor is the shaded-pole motor and is used in devices requiring low starting torque, such as electric fans, small pumps, or small household appliances.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In this motor, small single-turn copper "shading coils" create the moving magnetic field.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Part of each pole is encircled by a copper coil or strap; the induced current in the strap opposes the change of flux through the coil.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This causes a time lag in the flux passing through the shading coil, so that the maximum field intensity moves higher across the pole face on each cycle.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This produces a low level rotating magnetic field which is large enough to turn both the rotor and its attached load.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] As the rotor picks up speed the torque builds up to its full level as the principal magnetic field is rotating relative to the rotating rotor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A **reversible shaded-pole motor** was made by Barber-Colman several decades ago.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] It had a single field coil, and two principal poles, each split halfway to create two pairs of poles.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Each of these four "half-poles" carried a coil, and the coils of diagonally opposite half-poles were connected to a pair of terminals.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] One terminal of each pair was common, so only three terminals were needed in all.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The motor would not start with the terminals open; connecting the common to one made the motor run one way, and connecting the common to the other made it run the other way.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] These motors were used in industrial and scientific devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] An unusual, **adjustable-speed**, low-torque shaded-pole motor could be found in traffic-light and advertising-lighting controllers.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The pole faces were parallel and relatively close to each other, with the disc centered between them, something like the disc in a watthour electricity meter.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Each pole face was split, and had a shading coil on one part; the shading coils were on the parts that faced each other.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Applying AC to the coil created a field that progressed in the gap between the poles.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The plane of the stator core was approximately tangential to an imaginary circle on the disc, so the travelling magnetic field dragged the disc and made it rotate.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The stator was mounted on a pivot so it could be positioned for the desired speed and then clamped in position.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Placing the poles nearer to the center of the disc made it run faster, and toward the edge, slower.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Another common single-phase AC motor is the *split-phase induction motor*, commonly used in major appliances such as air conditioners and clothes dryers.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Compared to the shaded pole motor, these motors provide much greater starting torque.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A split-phase motor has a secondary startup winding that is 90 electrical degrees to the main winding, always centered directly between the poles of the main winding, and connected to the main winding by a set of electrical contacts.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The coils of this winding are wound with fewer turns of smaller wire than the main winding, so it has a lower inductance and higher resistance.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The position of the winding creates a small phase shift between the flux of the main winding and the flux of the starting winding, causing the rotor to rotate.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] When the speed of the motor is sufficient to overcome the inertia of the load, the contacts are opened automatically by a centrifugal switch or electric relay.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The direction of rotation is determined by the connection between the main winding and the start circuit.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In applications where the motor requires a fixed rotation, one end of the start circuit is permanently connected to the main winding, with the contacts making the connection at the other end.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A capacitor start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starting motor capacitor inserted in series with the startup winding, creating an LC circuit which produces a greater phase shift (and so, a much greater starting torque) than both split-phase and shaded pole motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This motor has a centrifugal switch which disconnects the capacitor once the motor has started.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque and high efficiency.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A resistance start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starter inserted in series with the startup winding, creating reactance.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This added starter provides assistance in the starting and initial direction of rotation.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The start winding is made mainly of thin wire with fewer turns to make it high resistive and less inductive.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The main winding is made with thicker wire with larger number of turns which makes it less resistive and more inductive.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Another variation is the *permanent-split capacitor (or PSC) motor*.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Also known as a capacitor-run motor, this type of motor uses a non-polarized capacitor with a high voltage rating to generate an electrical phase shift between the run and start windings.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] PSC motors are the dominant type of split-phase motor in Europe and much of the world, but in North America, they are most frequently used in variable torque applications (like blowers, fans, and pumps) and other cases where variable speeds are desired.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A capacitor with a relatively low capacitance, and relatively high voltage rating, is connected in series with the start winding and remains in the circuit during the entire run cycle.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Like other split-phase motors, the main winding is used with a smaller start winding, and rotation is changed by reversing the connection between the main winding and the start circuit, or by having polarity of main winding switched while start winding is always connected to a capacitor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] There are significant differences, however; the use of a speed sensitive centrifugal switch requires that other split-phase motors must operate at, or very close to, full speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] PSC motors may operate within a wide range of speeds, much lower than the motor's electrical speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Also, for applications like automatic door openers that require the motor to reverse rotation often, the use of a mechanism requires that a motor must slow to a near stop before contact with the start winding is re-established.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The 'permanent' connection to the capacitor in a PSC motor means that changing rotation is instantaneous.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Three-phase motors can be converted to PSC motors by making common two windings and connecting the third via a capacitor to act as a start winding.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] However, the power rating needs to be at least 50% larger than for a comparable single-phase motor due to an unused winding.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The synchronous motor can also be used as an alternator.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Contemporary synchronous motors are frequently driven by solid state variable-frequency drives.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This greatly eases the problem of starting the massive rotor of a large synchronous motor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are occasionally used as traction motors; the TGV may be the best-known example of such use.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Huge numbers of three phase synchronous motors are now fitted to electric cars.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] They have a neodymium or other rare-earth permanent magnet.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] One use for this type of motor is its use in a power factor correction scheme.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] They are referred to as synchronous condensers.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This exploits a feature of the machine where it consumes power at a leading power factor when its rotor is over excited.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] It thus appears to the supply to be a capacitor, and could thus be used to correct the lagging power factor that is usually presented to the electric supply by inductive loads.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The excitation is adjusted until a near unity power factor is obtained (often automatically).
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Machines used for this purpose are easily identified as they have no shaft extensions.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are valued in any case because their power factor is much better than that of induction motors, making them preferred for very high power applications.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Some of the largest AC motors are pumped-storage hydroelectricity generators that are operated as synchronous motors to pump water to a reservoir at a higher elevation for later use to generate electricity using the same machinery.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Six 500-megawatt generators are installed in the Bath County Pumped Storage Station in Virginia, USA.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] When pumping, each unit can produce 642,800 horsepower (479.3 megawatts).
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Small single-phase AC motors can also be designed with magnetized rotors (or several variations on that idea; see "Hysteresis synchronous motors" below).
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] If a conventional squirrel-cage rotor has flats ground on it to create salient poles and increase reluctance, it will start conventionally, but will run synchronously, although it can provide only a modest torque at synchronous speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Because inertia makes it difficult to instantly accelerate the rotor from stopped to synchronous speed, these motors normally require some sort of special feature to get started.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Some include a squirrel-cage structure to bring the rotor close to synchronous speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Various other designs use a small induction motor (which may share the same field coils and rotor as the synchronous motor) or a very light rotor with a one-way mechanism (to ensure that the rotor starts in the "forward" direction).
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In the latter instance, applying AC power creates chaotic (or seemingly chaotic) jumping movement back and forth; such a motor will always start, but lacking the anti-reversal mechanism, the direction it runs is unpredictable.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The Hammond organ tone generator used a non-self-starting synchronous motor (until comparatively recently), and had an auxiliary conventional shaded-pole starting motor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A spring-loaded auxiliary manual starting switch connected power to this second motor for a few seconds.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] These motors are relatively costly, and are used where exact speed (assuming an exact-frequency AC source) and rotation with low flutter (high-frequency variation in speed) are essential.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Applications included tape recorder capstan drives (the motor shaft could be the capstan), and, before the advent of crystal control, motion picture cameras and recorders.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Their distinguishing feature is their rotor, which is a smooth cylinder of a magnetic alloy that stays magnetized, but can be demagnetized fairly easily as well as re-magnetized with poles in a new location.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Hysteresis refers to how the magnetic flux in the metal lags behind the external magnetizing force; for instance, to demagnetize such a material, one could apply a magnetizing field of opposite polarity to that which originally magnetized the material.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] These motors have a stator like those of capacitor-run squirrel-cage induction motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] On startup, when slip decreases sufficiently, the rotor becomes magnetized by the stator's field, and the poles stay in place.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The motor then runs at synchronous speed as if the rotor were a permanent magnet.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] When stopped and restarted, the poles are likely to form at different locations.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] For a given design, torque at synchronous speed is only relatively modest, and the motor can run at below synchronous speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In simple words, it is lagging magnetic field behind magnetic flux.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A universal motor is a design that can operate on either AC or DC power.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In universal motors the stator and rotor of a brushed DC motor are both wound and supplied from an external source, with the torque being a function of the rotor current times the stator current so reversing the current in both rotor and stator does not reverse the rotation.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Universal motors can run on AC as well as DC provided the frequency is not so high that the inductive reactance of the stator winding and eddy current losses become problems.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Nearly all universal motors are series-wound because their stators have relatively few turns, minimizing inductance.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Universal motors are compact, have high starting torque and can be varied in speed over a wide range with relatively simple controls such as rheostats and PWM choppers.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Compared with induction motors, universal motors do have some drawbacks inherent to their brushes and commutators: relatively high levels of electrical and acoustic noise, low reliability and more frequent required maintenance.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Universal motors are widely used in small home appliances and hand power tools.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Until the 1970s they dominated electric traction (electric, including diesel-electric railway and road vehicles); many traction power networks still use special low frequencies such as 16.7 and 25 Hz to overcome the aforementioned problems with losses and reactance.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Still widely used, universal traction motors have been increasingly displaced by polyphase AC induction and permanent magnet motors with variable-frequency drives made possible by modern power semiconductor devices.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Repulsion motors are wound-rotor single-phase AC motors that are a type of induction motor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In a repulsion motor, the armature brushes are shorted together rather than connected in series with the field, as is done with universal motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] By transformer action, the stator induces currents in the rotor, which create torque by repulsion instead of attraction as in other motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Several types of repulsion motors have been manufactured, but the *repulsion-start induction-run* (RS-IR) motor has been used most frequently.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The RS-IR motor has a centrifugal switch that shorts all segments of the commutator so that the motor operates as an induction motor once it is close to full speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Some of these motors also lift the brushes out of contact with source voltage regulation.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Repulsion motors were developed before suitable motor starting capacitors were available, and few repulsion motors are sold as of 2005.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Where speed stability is important, some AC motors (such as some Papst motors) have the stator on the inside and the rotor on the outside to optimize inertia and cooling.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Exterior rotors are also common in ceiling fan motors.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A conical rotor brake motor incorporates the brake as an integral part of the conical sliding rotor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] When the motor is at rest, a spring acts on the sliding rotor and forces the brake ring against the brake cap in the motor, holding the rotor stationary.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] When the motor is energized, its magnetic field generates both an axial and a radial component.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The axial component overcomes the spring force, releasing the brake; while the radial component causes the rotor to turn.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] There is no additional brake control required.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The high starting torque and low inertia of the conical rotor brake motor has proven to be ideal for the demands of high cycle dynamic drives in applications since the motor was invented, designed and introduced over 50 years ago.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This type of motor configuration was first introduced in the US in 1963.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Single-speed or two speed motors are designed for coupling to gear motor system gearboxes.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Conical rotor brake motors are also used to power micro speed drives.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Motors of this type can also be found on overhead cranes and hoists.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines two motors and an intermediate gear reducer.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] These are used for applications where extreme mechanical positioning accuracy and high cycling capability are needed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines a “main” conical rotor brake motor for rapid speed and a “micro” conical rotor brake motor for slow or positioning speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The intermediate gearbox allows a range of ratios, and motors of different speeds can be combined to produce high ratios between high and low speed.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Electronically commutated (EC) motors are electric motors powered by direct-current (DC) electricity and having electronic commutation systems, rather than mechanical commutators and brushes.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The current-to-torque and frequency-to-speed relationships of BLDC motors are linear.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] While the motor coils are powered by DC, power may be rectified from AC within the casing.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] These are two-phase induction motors with permanent magnets to retard the rotor so its speed is accurately proportional to the power passing through the meter.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The rotor is an aluminium-alloy disc, and currents induced into it react with the field from the stator.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] A split-phase watthour electricity meter has a stator with three coils facing the disc.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The magnetic circuit is completed by a C-shaped core of permeable iron.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The "voltage" coil above the disc is in parallel with the supply; its many turns have a high inductance/resistance ratio (Q) so its current and magnetic field are the time integral of the applied voltage, lagging it by 90 degrees.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This magnetic field passes down perpendicularly through the disc, inducing circular eddy currents in the plane of the disc centered on the field.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] These induced currents are proportional to the time derivative of the magnetic field, leading it by 90 degrees.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This puts the eddy currents in phase with the voltage applied to the voltage coil, just as the current induced in the secondary of a transformer with a resistive load is in phase with the voltage applied to its primary.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The eddy currents pass directly above the pole pieces of two "current" coils under the disc, each wound with a few turns of heavy-gauge wire whose inductive reactance is small compared to the load impedance.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] These coils connect the supply to the load, producing a magnetic field in phase with the load current.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] This field passes from the pole of one current coil up perpendicularly through the disc and back down through the disc to the pole of the other current coil, with a completed magnetic circuit back to the first current coil.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] As these fields cross the disc, they pass through the eddy currents induced in it by the voltage coil producing a Lorentz force on the disc mutually perpendicular to both.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Assuming power is flowing to the load, the flux from the left current coil crosses the disc upwards where the eddy current flows radially toward the center of the disc producing (by the right-hand rule) a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Similarly, the flux crosses down through the disc to the right current coil where the eddy current flows radially away from the disc center, again producing a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] When the AC polarity reverses, the eddy currents in the disc and the direction of the magnetic flux from the current coils both change, leaving the direction of the torque unchanged.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The torque is thus proportional to the instantaneous line voltage times the instantaneous load current, automatically correcting for power factor.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The disc is braked by a permanent magnet so that speed is proportional to torque and the disc mechanically integrates real power.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The mechanical dial on the meter reads disc rotations and the total net energy delivered to the load.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In a split-phase watthour meter the voltage coil is connected between the two "hot" (line) terminals (240 V in North America) and two separate current coils are connected between the corresponding line and load terminals.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] No connection to the system neutral is needed to correctly handle combined line-to-neutral and line-to-line loads.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Line-to-line loads draw the same current through both current coils and spin the meter twice as fast as a line-to-neutral load drawing the same current through only a single current coil, correctly registering the power drawn by the line-to-line load as twice that of the line-to-neutral load.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Other variations of the same design are used for polyphase (e.g., three-phase) power.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Representative are low-torque synchronous motors with a multi-pole hollow cylindrical magnet (internal poles) surrounding the stator structure.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The stator has one coil, coaxial with the shaft.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] At each end of the coil are a pair of circular plates with rectangular teeth on their edges, formed so they are parallel with the shaft.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] One of the pair of discs distributes the coil's flux directly, while the other receives flux that has passed through a common shading coil.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] The poles are rather narrow, and between the poles leading from one end of the coil are an identical set leading from the other end.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] In all, this creates a repeating sequence of four poles, unshaded alternating with shaded, that creates a circumferential traveling field to which the rotor's magnetic poles rapidly synchronize.
[src:direct-current/ac-motor] Some stepping motors have a similar structure.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] A solid-state **AC-to-AC converter** converts an AC waveform to another AC waveform, where the output voltage and frequency can be set arbitrarily.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Any dynamic braking operation required for the motor can be realized by means of braking DC chopper and resistor shunt connected across the rectifier.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Alternatively, an anti-parallel thyristor bridge must be provided in the rectifier section to feed energy back into the AC line.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Such phase-controlled thyristor-based rectifiers however have higher AC line distortion and lower power factor at low load than diode-based rectifiers.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] An AC-AC converter with approximately sinusoidal input currents and bidirectional power flow can be realized by coupling a pulse-width modulation (PWM) rectifier and a PWM inverter to the DC-link.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] The DC-link quantity is then impressed by an energy storage element that is common to both stages, which is a capacitor C for the voltage DC-link or an inductor L for the current DC-link.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] The PWM rectifier is controlled in a way that a sinusoidal AC line current is drawn, which is in phase or anti-phase (for energy feedback) with the corresponding AC line phase voltage.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Due to the DC-link storage element, there is the advantage that both converter stages are to a large extent decoupled for control purposes.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Furthermore, a constant, AC line independent input quantity exists for the PWM inverter stage, which results in high utilization of the converter’s power capability.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] On the other hand, the DC-link energy storage element has a relatively large physical volume, and when electrolytic capacitors are used, in the case of a voltage DC-link, there is potentially a reduced system lifetime.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] A cycloconverter constructs an output, variable-frequency, approximately sinusoid waveform by switching segments of the input waveform to the output; there is no intermediate DC link.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] With switching elements such as SCRs, the output frequency must be lower than the input.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Very large cycloconverters (on the order of 10 MW) are manufactured for compressor and wind-tunnel drives, or for variable-speed applications such as cement kilns.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] In order to achieve higher power density and reliability, matrix converters are considered.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] They achieve three-phase AC-AC conversion without any intermediate energy storage element.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Conventional direct matrix converters (Fig.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] 4) perform voltage and current conversion in one single stage.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] There is the alternative option of indirect energy conversion by employing the Indirect Matrix Converter (Fig.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] 5) or the Sparse matrix converter which was invented by Prof.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] As with the DC-link based VSI and CSI controllers (Fig.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] 3), separate stages are provided for voltage and current conversion, but the DC-link has no intermediate storage element.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Generally, by employing matrix converters, the storage element in the DC-link is eliminated at the cost of a larger number of semiconductors.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] Matrix converters are often seen as a future concept for variable speed drives technology, but despite intensive research over the decades they have until now only achieved low industrial penetration.
[src:direct-current/ac-to-ac-converter] However, citing recent availability of low-cost, high performance semiconductors, one larger drive manufacturer has over past few years been actively promoting matrix converters.
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX is a commonly used motherboard and power supply hardware form factor for desktop computers.
[src:direct-current/atx] The ATX form factor defined a general mounting point placement and I/O panel size that smaller motherboards share (such as microATX, FlexATX, and Mini-ITX), making them backwards compatible in many computer cases.
[src:direct-current/atx] As of 2012, ATX is the most common motherboard design.
[src:direct-current/atx] Other standards for smaller boards (including microATX, FlexATX, nano-ITX, and mini-ITX) keep the basic rear layout but reduce the size of the board and the number of expansion slots.
[src:direct-current/atx] Dimensions of a full-size ATX board are 12 × 9.6 in (305 × 244 mm) which means microATX boards fit in many ATX chassis.
[src:direct-current/atx] The ATX specifications were patented by David Dent at Intel and co-developed with Astec America, a major manufacturer of power supplies at the time.
[src:direct-current/atx] The inaugural version 1.0 of the ATX specification was unveiled by Intel in July 1995.
[src:direct-current/atx] Since then, ATX has been revised numerous times.
[src:direct-current/atx] The most recent ATX motherboard specification is version 2.2.
[src:direct-current/atx] The most recent ATX12V power supply unit specification is ATX 3.0 released in February 2022.
[src:direct-current/atx] EATX, or E-ATX (Extended ATX), is a term that refers to motherboards larger than the ATX standard.
[src:direct-current/atx] Motherboards labeled E-ATX commonly share dimensions with the SSI-EEB (Server System Infrastructure - Enterprise Electronics Bay) standard (12 x 13 in), however, it is not a guarantee.
[src:direct-current/atx] While some dual-CPU-socket motherboards have been implemented in ATX, the extra size of EATX makes it the typical form factor for dual-socket systems and for single-socket systems with a large number of memory slots (or more than two memory channels).
[src:direct-current/atx] In 2004, Intel announced the BTX (Balanced Technology eXtended) standard, intended as a replacement for ATX.
[src:direct-current/atx] While some manufacturers adopted the new standard, Intel discontinued any future development of BTX in 2006.
[src:direct-current/atx] As of 2026, the ATX design still remains the standard for personal computers.
[src:direct-current/atx] On the back of the computer case, some major changes were made to the AT standard.
[src:direct-current/atx] Originally AT style cases had only a keyboard connector and expansion slots for add-on card backplates.
[src:direct-current/atx] Any other onboard interfaces (such as serial and parallel ports) had to be connected via flying leads to connectors which were mounted either on spaces provided by the case or brackets placed in unused expansion slot positions.
[src:direct-current/atx] The ATX standard specified a rectangular area on the back of the system where motherboard manufacturers can arrange ports any way they want.
[src:direct-current/atx] A number of general patterns (depending on which ports the motherboard offers) have been used by most manufacturers.
[src:direct-current/atx] Cases are usually fitted with a snap-out panel, also known as an I/O plate or I/O shield, in one of the common arrangements.
[src:direct-current/atx] I/O plates are usually included with retail motherboards for installation in any suitable case.
[src:direct-current/atx] The computer will operate correctly without a plate fitted, but there will be open gaps in the case which may compromise the EMI/RFI screening and allow the ingress of dirt and random foreign bodies.
[src:direct-current/atx] Panels were made that fit an AT motherboard in an ATX case.
[src:direct-current/atx] Some ATX motherboards come with an integrated I/O plate.
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX also made the PS/2-style mini-DIN keyboard and mouse connectors ubiquitous.
[src:direct-current/atx] AT systems used a 5-pin DIN connector for the keyboard and were generally used with serial port mice (although PS/2 mouse ports were also found on some systems).
[src:direct-current/atx] Many modern motherboards are phasing out the PS/2-style keyboard and mouse connectors in favor of the more modern Universal Serial Bus.
[src:direct-current/atx] Other legacy connectors that are slowly being phased out of modern ATX motherboards include 25-pin parallel ports and 9-pin RS-232 serial ports.
[src:direct-current/atx] In their place are onboard peripheral ports such as Ethernet, FireWire, eSATA, audio ports (both analog and S/PDIF), video (analog D-sub, DVI, HDMI, or DisplayPort), extra USB ports, and Wi-Fi.
[src:direct-current/atx] A notable issue with the ATX specification was that it was last revised when power supplies were normally placed at the top of many old computer cases rather than at the bottom, as with many modern computer cases.
[src:direct-current/atx] This has led to some problematic standard locations for ports, in particular the 4/8 pin CPU power, which is normally located along the top edge of the board, convenient for top-mounted power supplies.
[src:direct-current/atx] This makes it very difficult for cables from bottom-mounted power supplies to reach, and commonly requires a special cutout in the back plane for the cable to come in from behind and bend around the board, making insertion and wire management very difficult.
[src:direct-current/atx] Many power supply cables barely or fail to reach, or are too stiff to make the bend, and extensions are sometimes required due to this placement.
[src:direct-current/atx] Modern power supplies often have longer cables to alleviate this issue.
[src:direct-current/atx] Several ATX-derived designs have been specified that use the same power supply, mountings and basic back panel arrangement, but set different standards for the size of the board and number of expansion slots.
[src:direct-current/atx] Standard ATX provides seven slots at 0.8 in (20 mm) spacing; the popular microATX size removes 2.4 inches (61 mm) and three slots, leaving four.
[src:direct-current/atx] Here width refers to the distance along the external connector edge, while depth is from front to rear.
[src:direct-current/atx] Note each larger size inherits all previous (smaller) colors area.
[src:direct-current/atx] AOpen has conflated the term Mini ATX with a more recent 15 × 15 cm (5.9 × 5.9 in) design.
[src:direct-current/atx] Since references to Mini ATX have been removed from ATX specifications since the adoption of microATX, the AOpen definition is the more contemporary term and the one listed above is apparently only of historical significance.
[src:direct-current/atx] This sounds contradictory to the now common Mini-ITX standard (17 × 17 cm (6.7 × 6.7 in)), which is a potential source of confusion.
[src:direct-current/atx] A number of manufacturers have added one to three additional expansion slots (at the standard 0.8 inch spacing) to the standard 12-inch ATX motherboard width.
[src:direct-current/atx] Form factors considered obsolete in 1999 included Baby-AT, full size AT, and the semi-proprietary LPX for low-profile cases.
[src:direct-current/atx] Proprietary motherboard designs such as those by Compaq, Packard-Bell, Hewlett Packard and others existed, and were not interchangeable with multi-manufacturer boards and cases.
[src:direct-current/atx] Portable and notebook computers and some 19-inch rackmount servers have custom motherboards unique to their particular products.
[src:direct-current/atx] While E-ATX and SSI EEB (Server System Infrastructure (SSI) Forum's Enterprise Electronics Bay (EEB)) share the same dimensions, the screw holes of the two standards do not all align; rendering them incompatible.
[src:direct-current/atx] In 2008, Foxconn unveiled a Foxconn F1 motherboard prototype, which has the same width as a standard ATX motherboard, but an extended 14.4" length to accommodate 10 slots.
[src:direct-current/atx] The firm called the new 14.4 × 9.6 in (366 × 244 mm) design of this motherboard "Ultra ATX" in its CES 2008 showing.
[src:direct-current/atx] Also unveiled during the January 2008 CES was the Lian Li Armorsuit PC-P80 case with 10 slots designed for the motherboard.
[src:direct-current/atx] In 2010, EVGA Corporation released a new motherboard, the "Super Record 2", or SR-2, whose size surpasses that of the "EVGA X58 Classified 4-Way SLI".
[src:direct-current/atx] The new board is designed to accommodate two Dual QPI LGA1366 socket CPUs (e.g.
[src:direct-current/atx] Intel Xeon), similar to that of the Intel Skulltrail motherboard that could accommodate two Intel Core 2 Quad processors and has a total of seven PCI-E slots and 12 DDR3 RAM slots.
[src:direct-current/atx] The ATX specification requires the power supply to produce three main outputs, +3.3 V, +5 V and +12 V.
[src:direct-current/atx] Low-power −12 V and +5 VSB (standby) supplies are also required.
[src:direct-current/atx] The −12 V supply is primarily used to provide the negative supply voltage for RS-232 ports and is also used by one pin on conventional PCI slots primarily to provide a reference voltage for some models of sound cards.
[src:direct-current/atx] The 5 VSB supply is used to produce trickle power to provide the soft-power feature of ATX when a PC is turned off, as well as powering the real-time clock to conserve the charge of the CMOS battery.
[src:direct-current/atx] A −5 V output was originally required because it was supplied on the ISA bus.
[src:direct-current/atx] However, it was removed in later versions of the ATX standard once ISA expansion slots became obsolete.
[src:direct-current/atx] Originally, the motherboard was powered by one 20-pin connector.
[src:direct-current/atx] An ATX power supply provides a number of peripheral power connectors and (in modern systems) two connectors for the motherboard: an 8-pin (or 4+4-pin) auxiliary connector providing additional power to the CPU and a main 24-pin power supply connector, an extension of the original 20-pin version.
[src:direct-current/atx] The connector pin pitch is 4.20 mm (about one sixth of an inch).
[src:direct-current/atx] Generally, supply voltages must be within ±5% of their nominal values at all times.
[src:direct-current/atx] The little-used negative supply voltages, however, have a ±10% tolerance.
[src:direct-current/atx] The 20–24-pin Molex Mini-Fit Jr. has a power rating of, 9 amperes maximum per pin).
[src:direct-current/atx] As large server motherboards and 3D graphics cards have required progressively more and more power to operate, it has been necessary to revise and extend the standard beyond the original 20-pin connector, to allow more current using multiple additional pins in parallel.
[src:direct-current/atx] The low circuit voltage is the restriction on power flow through each connector pin; at the maximum rated voltage, a single Mini-Fit Jr pin would be capable of 4800 watts.
[src:direct-current/atx] That last dimension, the 140 mm depth, is frequently varied, with depths of 160, 180, 200 and 230 mm used to accommodate higher power, larger fan and/or modular connectors.
[src:direct-current/atx] Original AT cases (flat case style) have an integrated power switch that protruded from the power supply and sits flush with a hole in the AT chassis.
[src:direct-current/atx] It utilizes a paddle-style DPST switch and is similar to the PC and PC-XT style power supplies.
[src:direct-current/atx] Later AT (so-called "Baby AT") and LPX style computer cases have a power button that is directly connected to the system computer power supply (PSU).
[src:direct-current/atx] The general configuration is a double-pole latching mains voltage switch with the four pins connected to wires from a four-core cable.
[src:direct-current/atx] The wires are either soldered to the power button (making it difficult to replace the power supply if it failed) or blade receptacles were used.
[src:direct-current/atx] An ATX power supply is typically controlled by an electronic switch connected to the power button on the computer case and allows the computer to be turned off by the operating system.
[src:direct-current/atx] In addition, many ATX power supplies have a manual switch on the back that also ensures no power is being sent to the components.
[src:direct-current/atx] When the switch on the power supply is turned off, the computer cannot be turned on with the front power button.
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX uses one large, keyed connector which can not be connected incorrectly.
[src:direct-current/atx] The new connector also provides a 3.3 volt source, removing the need for motherboards to derive this voltage from the 5 V rail.
[src:direct-current/atx] Some motherboards, particularly those manufactured after the introduction of ATX but whilst LPX equipment was still in use, support both LPX and ATX PSUs.
[src:direct-current/atx] A minimum load on one or more voltages may be required (varies by model and vendor); the standard does not specify operation without a minimum load and a conforming PSU may shut down, output incorrect voltages, or otherwise malfunction, but will not be hazardous or damaged.
[src:direct-current/atx] An ATX power supply is not a replacement for a current-limited bench laboratory DC power supply; instead it is better described as a bulk DC power supply.
[src:direct-current/atx] The original ATX specification called for a power supply to be located near to the CPU with the power supply fan drawing in cooling air from outside the chassis and directing it onto the processor.
[src:direct-current/atx] It was thought that in this configuration, cooling of the processor would be achievable without the need of an active heatsink.
[src:direct-current/atx] This recommendation was removed from later specifications; modern ATX power supplies usually exhaust air from the case.
[src:direct-current/atx] The power distribution specification defined that most of the PSU's power should be provided on 5 V and 3.3 V rails, because most of the electronic components (CPU, RAM, chipset, PCI, AGP and ISA cards) used 5 V or 3.3 V for power supply.
[src:direct-current/atx] While designing the Pentium 4 platform in 1999/2000, the standard 20-pin ATX power connector was found insufficient to meet increasing power-line requirements; the standard was significantly revised into ATX12V 1.0 (ATX12V 1.x is sometimes inaccurately called ATX-P4).
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX12V 1.x was also adopted by AMD Athlon XP and Athlon 64 systems.
[src:direct-current/atx] However, some early model Athlon XP and MP boards (including some server boards) and later model lower-end motherboards do not have the 4-pin connector as described below.
[src:direct-current/atx] Numbering of the ATX revisions may be a little confusing: ATX refers to the design, and goes up to version 2.2 in 2004 (with the 24 pins of ATX12V 2.0), while ATX12V describes only the PSU.
[src:direct-current/atx] For instance, ATX 2.03 is quite commonly seen on PSUs from 2000 and 2001 and often includes the P4 12V connector, even if the norm itself did not define it yet.
[src:direct-current/atx] Formally called the *+12 V Power Connector*, this is commonly referred to as the **P4 connector** because this was first needed to support the Pentium 4 processor.
[src:direct-current/atx] Before the Pentium 4, processors were generally powered from the 5 V rail.
[src:direct-current/atx] Later processors operate at much lower voltages, typically around 1 V and some draw over 100 A.
[src:direct-current/atx] It is infeasible to provide power at such low voltages and high currents from a standard system power supply, so the Pentium 4 established the practice of generating it with a DC-to-DC converter on the motherboard next to the processor, powered by the 4-pin 12 V connector.
[src:direct-current/atx] This is a minor revision from August 2000.
[src:direct-current/atx] The power on the 3.3 V rail was slightly increased and other smaller changes were made.
[src:direct-current/atx] A relatively minor revision from January 2002.
[src:direct-current/atx] The only significant change was that the −5 V rail was no longer required (it became optional).
[src:direct-current/atx] This voltage was required by the ISA bus, which is no longer present on almost all modern computers.
[src:direct-current/atx] Introduced in April 2003 (a month after 2.0).
[src:direct-current/atx] This standard introduced some changes, mostly minor.
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX12V 2.x brought a significant design change regarding power distribution.
[src:direct-current/atx] By analyzing the power demands of then-current PCs, it was determined that it would be much cheaper and more practical to power most PC components from 12 V rails, instead of from 3.3 V and 5 V rails.
[src:direct-current/atx] In particular, PCI Express expansion cards take much of their power from the 12 V rail (up to 5.5 A), while the older AGP graphics cards took only up to 1 A on 12 V and up to 6 A on 3.3 V.
[src:direct-current/atx] The CPU is also driven by a 12 V rail, while it was done by a 5 V rail on older PCs (before the Pentium 4).
[src:direct-current/atx] This is a minor revision from June 2004.
[src:direct-current/atx] An errant reference for the −5 V rail was removed.
[src:direct-current/atx] This is a minor revision from March 2005.
[src:direct-current/atx] The power was slightly increased on all rails.
[src:direct-current/atx] Efficiency requirements changed: minimum 65% at light load, 72% at typical load, and 70% at full load.
[src:direct-current/atx] Introduced recommended minimum values of 75% at light load, 80% at typical load, and 77% at full load.
[src:direct-current/atx] Also released in March 2005 it includes corrections and specifies High Current Series wire terminals for 24-pin ATX motherboard and 4-pin +12 V power connectors.
[src:direct-current/atx] Recommended efficiency was increased to 80% (with at least 70% required) and the 12 V minimum load requirement was lowered.
[src:direct-current/atx] Higher efficiency generally results in less power consumption (and less waste heat) and the 80% recommendation brings supplies in line with new Energy Star 4.0 mandates.
[src:direct-current/atx] The reduced load requirement allows compatibility with processors that draw very little power during startup.
[src:direct-current/atx] The absolute over-current limit of 240 VA per rail was removed, allowing 12 V lines to provide more than 20 A per rail.
[src:direct-current/atx] This revision became effective in February 2008.
[src:direct-current/atx] The ATX12V 2.4 specifications were published in August 2012.
[src:direct-current/atx] It is specified in Revision 1.31 of the *Power Supply Design Guide for Desktop Platform Form Factors*, which names this as ATX12V version 2.4.
[src:direct-current/atx] In July 2012, revision 1.3 of the *Power Supply Design Guide for Desktop Platform Form Factors* made inclusion of the floppy drive connector optional, instead of mandatory.
[src:direct-current/atx] The specifications for ATXV12 2.51 were released in September 2021 and introduced support for *Alternative Low Power Mode (ALPM)* which supersedes the traditional S3 power state.
[src:direct-current/atx] Windows 10 implements this functionality as *Modern Standby*.
[src:direct-current/atx] Power supply fans are also recommended to turn on with at least a two second delay for an improved user experience.
[src:direct-current/atx] This version also stated that the floppy drive connector should be excluded from PSUs, as opposed to merely being optional, and marked that connector's section in the specification as "For Historical Reference Only".
[src:direct-current/atx] The specifications for ATX12V 2.53 were released in December 2021 and constitute another minor update to the ATX standard.
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX12V 2.53 makes further recommendations on efficiency and references the Energy Star *Computers Specification Version 8.0* which was finalized in April 2020.
[src:direct-current/atx] The specifications for ATX 3.0 were released in February 2022.
[src:direct-current/atx] It includes the new 16-pin 12VHPWR connector that can deliver up to 600 W for H+ and up to 675 W in H++ to graphics cards.
[src:direct-current/atx] These incorporate data lines for components to negotiate power capabilities with the PSU so they do not draw more power than the PSU is capable of delivering.
[src:direct-current/atx] The specification also has more strict requirements for handling spikes, two times the nominal output for 100 microseconds.
[src:direct-current/atx] The −12 V supply is now specified as optional on the ATX motherboard connector, and some PSU manufacturers (e.g.
[src:direct-current/atx] Corsair) have begun removing the −12 V supply from their PSUs.
[src:direct-current/atx] However, as of 2025, some motherboards (e.g. recent designs from ASRock) still use the −12 V supply - typically to power the amplifier for on-board audio - and functions that use it will not work as expected when paired with a PSU that does not provide a −12 V supply.
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX 3.1 replaces the 12VHPWR power connector with the 12V-2x6 power connector and reduces required power loss hold-up time from 17 milliseconds to 12 milliseconds.
[src:direct-current/atx] Standing for **ATX 12-volt-only**, this is a new specification published by Intel in 2019, aimed at pre-built systems in the first run, and stricter power efficiency requirements by the California Energy Commission going into effect in 2021.
[src:direct-current/atx] Several OEMs were already using a similar design with proprietary connectors and this effectively standardizes those.
[src:direct-current/atx] Under this standard, power supplies provide only a 12 V output.
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX12VO introduces a new 10-pin connector to supply the motherboard, replacing the 24-pin ATX12V connector.
[src:direct-current/atx] This greatly simplifies power supplies, but moves DC-to-DC conversion and some connectors to the motherboard instead.
[src:direct-current/atx] Notably, SATA power connectors, which include 3.3 V and 5 V pins, need to move to the motherboard instead of being connected directly to the power supply.
[src:direct-current/atx] Connector pinout per Intel ATX12VO (12V Only) Desktop Power Supply Design Guide.
[src:direct-current/atx] SFX (Small Form-Factor eXtended) is merely a design for a small form factor (SFF) power supply casing (such as those using microATX, FlexATX, nano-ITX, mini-ITX, and NLX), with the power specifications almost identical to ATX.
[src:direct-current/atx] Thus, an SFX power supply is mostly pin-compatible with the ATX power supply as the main difference is its reduced dimensions; the only electrical difference is that the SFX specifications do not require the −5 V rail.
[src:direct-current/atx] Since −5 V is required only by some ISA-bus expansion cards, this is not an issue with modern hardware and decreases productions costs.
[src:direct-current/atx] As a result, ATX pin 20, which carried −5 V, is absent in current power supplies; it was optional in ATX and ATX12V version 1.2 and deleted as of ATX version 1.3.
[src:direct-current/atx] SFX has dimensions of 125 × 63.5 × 100 mm (width × height × depth), with a 60 mm fan, compared with the standard ATX dimensions of 150 × 86 × 140 mm.
[src:direct-current/atx] Optional 80 or 40 mm fan replacement increases or decreases the height of an SFX unit.
[src:direct-current/atx] Some manufacturers and retailers incorrectly market SFX power supplies as μATX or MicroATX power supplies.
[src:direct-current/atx] Some manufacturers make SFX-L dimensions of 125 × 63.5 × 130 mm to accommodate a 120 mm fan.
[src:direct-current/atx] Thin Form Factor is another small power supply design with standard ATX specification connectors.
[src:direct-current/atx] WTX power supplies provide a WTX style motherboard connector which is incompatible with the standard ATX motherboard connector.
[src:direct-current/atx] This is an ATX12V power supply derivative made by AMD to power its Athlon MP (dual processor) platform.
[src:direct-current/atx] It was used only on high-end Athlon MP motherboards.
[src:direct-current/atx] It has a special 8-pin supplemental connector for motherboard, so an AMD GES PSU is required for such motherboards (those motherboards will not work with ATX(12 V) PSUs).
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX12V-GES 24-pin P1 motherboard connector.
[src:direct-current/atx] ATX12V-GES 8-pin P2 motherboard connector.
[src:direct-current/atx] EPS12V is defined in Server System Infrastructure (SSI) and used primarily by SMP/multi-core systems such as Core 2, Core i7, Opteron and Xeon.
[src:direct-current/atx] It has a 24-pin ATX motherboard connector (same as ATX12V v2.x), an 8-pin secondary connector and an optional 4-pin tertiary connector.
[src:direct-current/atx] Rather than include the extra cable, many power supply makers implement the 8-pin connector as two combinable 4-pin connectors to ensure backwards compatibility with ATX12V motherboards.
[src:direct-current/atx] High-performance video card power demands dramatically increased during the 2000s and some high-end graphics cards have power demands that exceed AGP or PCIe slot capabilities.
[src:direct-current/atx] For these cards, supplementary power was delivered through a standard 4-pin peripheral or floppy power connector.
[src:direct-current/atx] Midrange and high-end PCIe graphics cards manufactured after 2004 typically use a standard 6- or 8-pin PCIe power connector directly from the PSU.
[src:direct-current/atx] Efficiency in power supplies means the extent to which power is not wasted in converting electricity from a household supply to regulated DC.
[src:direct-current/atx] Computer power supplies vary from around 70% to over 90% efficiency.
[src:direct-current/atx] Various initiatives exist to improve the efficiency of computer power supplies.
[src:direct-current/atx] Climate Savers Computing Initiative promotes energy saving and reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by encouraging development and use of more efficient power supplies.
[src:direct-current/atx] 80 PLUS certifies a variety of efficiency levels for power supplies and encourages their use via financial incentives.
[src:direct-current/atx] Efficient power supplies also save money by wasting less power; as a result they use less electricity to power the same computer, and they emit less waste heat which results in significant energy savings on central air conditioning in the summer.
[src:direct-current/atx] The gains of using an efficient power supply are more substantial in computers that use a lot of power.
[src:direct-current/atx] Although a power supply with a larger than needed power rating will have an extra margin of safety against overloading, such a unit is often less efficient and wastes more electricity at lower loads than a more appropriately sized unit.
[src:direct-current/atx] Thus, for a 100 W load, losses for this supply would be 27 W; if the same power supply was put under a 450 W load, for which the supply's efficiency peaks at 89%, the loss would be only 56 W despite supplying 4.5 times the useful power.
[src:direct-current/atx] For a comparison, a 500-watt power supply carrying the 80 Plus Bronze efficiency rating (which means that such a power supply is designed to be at least 82-percent efficient for loads above 100 W) may provide an 84 percent efficiency for a 100 W load, wasting only 19 W.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The abbreviations *AC* and *DC* are often used to mean simply *alternating* and *direct*, as when they modify *current* or *voltage*.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Direct current may be converted from an alternating current supply by use of a rectifier, which contains electronic elements (usually) or electromechanical elements (historically) that allow current to flow only in one direction.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Direct current may be converted into alternating current via an inverter.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Direct current has many uses, from the charging of batteries to large power supplies for electronic systems, motors, and more.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Very large quantities of electrical energy provided via direct-current are used in smelting of aluminum and other electrochemical processes.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] It is also used for some railways, especially in urban areas.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] High-voltage direct current is used to transmit large amounts of power from remote generation sites or to interconnect alternating current power grids.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Direct current was produced in 1800 by Italian physicist Alessandro Volta's battery, his Voltaic pile.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The nature of how current flowed was not yet understood.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] French physicist André-Marie Ampère conjectured that current travelled in one direction from positive to negative.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] When French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii built the first dynamo electric generator in 1832, he found that as the magnet used passed the loops of wire each half turn, it caused the flow of electricity to reverse, generating an alternating current.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] At Ampère's suggestion, Pixii later added a commutator, a type of "switch" where contacts on the shaft work with "brush" contacts to produce direct current.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The late 1870s and early 1880s saw electricity starting to be generated at power stations.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] These were initially set up to power arc lighting (a popular type of street lighting) running on very high voltage (usually higher than 3,000 volts) direct current or alternating current.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] This was followed by the widespread use of low voltage direct current for indoor electric lighting in business and homes after inventor Thomas Edison launched his incandescent bulb based electric "utility" in 1882.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Because of the significant advantages of alternating current over direct current in using transformers to raise and lower voltages to allow much longer transmission distances, direct current was replaced over the next few decades by alternating current in power delivery.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] In the mid-1950s, high-voltage direct current transmission was developed, and is now an option instead of long-distance high voltage alternating current systems.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] For long distance undersea cables (e.g. between countries, such as NorNed), this DC option is the only technically feasible option.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] For applications requiring direct current, such as third rail power systems, alternating current is distributed to a substation, which utilizes a rectifier to convert the power to direct current.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The term *DC* is used to refer to power systems that use only one electrical polarity of voltage or current, and to refer to the constant, zero-frequency, or slowly varying local mean value of a voltage or current.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] For example, the voltage across a DC voltage source is constant as is the current through a direct current source.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The DC solution of an electric circuit is the solution where all voltages and currents are constant.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Any stationary voltage or current waveform can be decomposed into a sum of a DC component and a zero-mean time-varying AC component; the DC component is defined to be the expected value, or the average value of the voltage or current over all time.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Although DC stands for "direct current", DC often refers to "constant polarity".
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Under this definition, DC voltages can vary in time, as seen in the raw output of a rectifier or the fluctuating voice signal on a telephone line.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Some forms of DC (such as that produced by a voltage regulator) have almost no variations in voltage, but may still have variations in output power and current.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] A direct current circuit is an electrical circuit that consists of any combination of constant voltage sources, constant current sources, and resistors.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] In this case, the circuit voltages and currents are independent of time.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] A particular circuit voltage or current does not depend on the past value of any circuit voltage or current.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] This implies that the system of equations that represent a DC circuit do not involve integrals or derivatives with respect to time.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] If a capacitor or inductor is added to a DC circuit, the resulting circuit is not, strictly speaking, a DC circuit.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] However, most such circuits have a DC solution.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] This solution gives the circuit voltages and currents when the circuit is in DC steady state.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Such a circuit is represented by a system of differential equations.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The solution to these equations usually contain a time varying or transient part as well as constant or steady state part.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] It is this steady state part that is the DC solution.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] There are some circuits that do not have a DC solution.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Two simple examples are a constant current source connected to a capacitor and a constant voltage source connected to an inductor.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] In electronics, it is common to refer to a circuit that is powered by a DC voltage source such as a battery or the output of a DC power supply as a DC circuit even though what is meant is that the circuit is DC powered.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] In a DC circuit, a power source (e.g. a battery, capacitor, etc.) has a positive and negative terminal, and likewise, the load also has a positive and negative terminal.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] To complete the circuit, positive charges need to flow from the power source to the load.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The charges will then return to the negative terminal of the load, which will then flow back to the negative terminal of the battery, completing the circuit.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] If either the positive or negative terminal is disconnected, the circuit will not be complete and the charges will not flow.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] In some DC circuit applications, polarity does not matter, which means you can connect positive and negative backwards and the circuit will still be complete and the load will still function normally.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] However, in most DC applications, polarity does matter, and connecting the circuit backwards will result in the load not working properly.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] DC is commonly found in many extra-low voltage applications and some low-voltage applications, especially where these are powered by batteries or solar power systems (since both can produce only DC).
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Most electronic circuits or devices require a DC power supply.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Domestic DC installations usually have different types of sockets, connectors, switches, and fixtures from those suitable for alternating current.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] This is mostly due to the lower voltages used, resulting in higher currents to produce the same amount of power.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] It is usually important with a DC appliance to observe polarity, unless the device has a diode bridge to correct for this.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] An automotive battery provides power for engine starting, lighting, the ignition system, the climate controls, and the infotainment system among others.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The alternator is an AC device which uses a rectifier to produce DC for battery charging.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Most highway passenger vehicles use nominally 12 V systems.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Many heavy trucks, farm equipment, or earth moving equipment with Diesel engines use 24 volt systems.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] In some older vehicles, 6 V was used, such as in the original classic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] At one point a 42 V electrical system was considered for automobiles, but this found little use.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] To save weight and wire, often the metal frame of the vehicle is connected to one pole of the battery and used as the return conductor in a circuit.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Often the negative pole is the chassis "ground" connection, but positive ground may be used in some wheeled or marine vehicles.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] In a battery electric vehicle, there are usually two separate DC systems.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The "low voltage" DC system typically operates at 12V, and serves the same purpose as in an internal combustion engine vehicle.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The "high voltage" system operates at 300-400V (depending on the vehicle), and provides the power for the traction motors.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Increasing the voltage for the traction motors reduces the current flowing through them, increasing efficiency.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Telephone exchange communication equipment uses standard −48 V DC power supply.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] The negative polarity is achieved by grounding the positive terminal of power supply system and the battery bank.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] This is done to prevent electrolysis depositions.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Telephone installations have a battery system to ensure power is maintained for subscriber lines during power interruptions.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Other devices may be powered from the telecommunications DC system using a DC-DC converter to provide any convenient voltage.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Many telephones connect to a twisted pair of wires, and use a bias tee to internally separate the AC component of the voltage between the two wires (the audio signal) from the DC component of the voltage between the two wires (used to power the phone).
[src:direct-current/direct-current] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems use DC for the bulk transmission of electrical power, in contrast with the more common alternating current systems.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] For long-distance transmission, HVDC systems may be less expensive and suffer lower electrical losses.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Applications using fuel cells (mixing hydrogen and oxygen together with a catalyst to produce electricity and water as byproducts) also produce only DC.
[src:direct-current/direct-current] Light aircraft electrical systems are typically 12 V or 24 V DC similar to automobiles.
